    Door-to-Door Waste Collection
</div>

Introduction

Separate waste collection is a key component in sustainable waste management.

Studying the impact of door-to-door collection can offer insights into changes in citizen behavior regarding waste management.

Door-to-door collection can have significant implications for operational costs and the economic efficiency of the waste management system. Understanding if this practice leads to greater efficiency or long-term cost reduction can justify initial investments and guide budget decisions.

On the other side, it can also influence social cohesion and community sense, as it often requires greater collaboration and participation from residents. Studying this aspect can reveal positive effects on civic engagement and collective responsibility.

My colleagues Andrea Tononi and Matteo Ricca and I developed a DID analysis to understand benefits and their extence of the introduction of door-to door collection as methodology of separate waste management.

What is the impact of the introduction of door-to-door separate waste collection on the overall rate of separate waste collection in various municipality in Northern Italy?

In 2021, slightly more than 73% of households reported being served by door-to-door waste collection (up from 66% in 2018). The average level of satisfaction with the service has been good and stable in recent years.

Datasets used

To perform our analysis we manually created a dataset using ISPRA and Legambiente 2024 report data. The clusterization is at municipality level. The data from the province of each municipality has not been taken in consideration. This is because the policy is introduced at this level, it is not mandatory that in the same province all the municipality use door-to-door collection for separate waste management. This ensure the compatibility between population: with other level of clusterization the differences may create a selection bias.

Is important to underline that our collection of data starts from 2010. Cities such as Bergamo which introduced the policy before that year are assessed symply by starting from an higher value in year_ind variable.

In order to evaluate performance over time we introduced a variable for the policy-start date. Dates has been extracted from web research and municipality legislation documents.

Which cities as been taken into analysis?

As already said only municipalities has been taken in consideration. A difference-in-difference approach, as many others impact evaluations methods, requires a treatment group (in our case the group of cities using door-to-door approach) and a control group (cities that have never introduced it).

Of particular importance is the Modena case. The original analysis has been made with data till 2022. In order to aggregate the 2023 data we have to assess that Modena started door-to-door collection in the end of 2023. Being the data comprehensive of all the 2023 waste management, and being the new methodology introduced only at december of the same year, we can conclude that is not significant in the overall results

Preliminar assumptions

  • The parallel trend assumption holds for each of the municipality till the policy introduction.
  • The mandatory imposition of type of recycling ensure there is not partial compliance
  • Recycling and waste collection are made in the same way for every municipality or the differences are not significant
  • The treatment is time invariant after the policy introduction

The assumptions can be summarized in

  1. Time invariant assumption
  2. Homogeneus treatment effect
  3. No partial compliance

Thanks to these assumption we can asses that Average Treatment on Treated is equal to Average Treatment on Untreated that is equal to Average Treatment Effecct (ATT=ATU=ATE), therefore we can use the average ATE as result for our model.

Empirical Approach

The following difference-in-differences (DID) regression model analyze the impact of door-to-door separate waste collection, we can use the following model specification:

\[ RD_{it} = \alpha + \beta_1 \cdot DID_{it} + \mathbf{X}_{it} + \varepsilon_{it} \] Where:

  • \(\mathbf{RD}_{it}\) is the percentage of separate waste collection in municipality \(i\) at time \(t\).

  • \(\mathbf{DID}_{it}\) is the interaction term that captures the differential effect of the policy on treated municipalities over time.

  • \(\mathbf{X}_{it}\) represents a vector of control variables that may influence the percentage of separate waste collection (e.g., mean waste quantity, population density, etc.).

  • \(\varepsilon_{it}\) is the error term.

# Import data
data = read_excel('Data.xlsx', sheet = "data") 
data <- as.data.frame(data)

# Create treatment indicator (did)
data['did'] = ifelse(data$year_ind > 0, 1, 0)

Visualizze the data

This is important to understand because in 2006 a legislative decree has been introduced to set a national objective of waste recycling for the year 2012: even if not all of the municipalities managed to achieve the objective proposed, financial found has been provided to the municipalities. Therefore:

  • Reciclying in general may be higher after that law due to mandatory higher recycling responsability
  • Effect of door-to-door policy before that year may be lower

Treatment and Control Groups Over Time

Lets visualize how our treatment and control groups change over time (base year = policy introduction).

# Summarize data by location, year, and treatment status
df_summary <- data %>%
  group_by(loc, year_ind, did) %>%
  summarise(mean_RD = mean(RD, na.rm = TRUE))

# Plot treatment and control over years
ggplot(df_summary, aes(x = year_ind, y = mean_RD, group = loc, color = factor(did))) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "R&D Trends by Treatment and Time",
    x = "Year Index",
    y = "Mean R&D Investment",
    color = "Treatment Status"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold")
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks = seq(-13, 17, by = 1),
    labels = function(x) ifelse(x %% 2 == 0, x, ""),
    expand = c(0, 0.1)
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("0" = "#3A86FF", "1" = "#FF006E"),
    labels = c("0" = "Control", "1" = "Treatment")
  )

The graph shows how the introduction of the policy drastically improve the total waste sorting management. As said above some cities introduced their policy before 2010 and those are the one where the treatment point start after the year 0 on the X axis.

Empirical Results

Finally, lets estimate the difference-in-differences model:

# Simple DiD model
mod1 <- lm(RD ~ did, data = data)

# Calculate robust standard errors
mod1_ro_se <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(mod1, type = "HC1")))

# Display results with robust standard errors
stargazer(mod1, type = "text", se = list(mod1_ro_se), 
          digits = 6, header = FALSE,
          title = "Difference-in-Differences Estimation Results",
          notes = "Heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors in parentheses")

Empirical results shows how significance is the introduction of our policy in terms of percentage on sorted waste.

As we can see an average effect of 21.07% is attributable to the policy introduction.

In fact, did represents the average difference between the treatment and control in the change in the outcome variable (RD) before and after the introduction of the treatment. Therefore this represents our ATE.

Constant: represents the avarage of RD for those cities where there is not door-to-door collection.

Conclusion

The introduction of the door-to-door collection waste have a positive and significant impact on the treated group compared to the control group.

In particular the average effects of treated groups (who introduce door-to-door collection policy) show a medium increase of slightly more above 21% in recycling disposal percentage.

The population of each municipality and the overall production of waste do not affect the results.

Possible weaknesses

We take into consideration just cities of the northern and center Italy, therefore it cannot be extended to all of the country as there are more differences not taken into account.

The percentage of waste collected depends also on factors that are difficult to measure and for this reason we did not include them, like for example the education and citizen awareness.
